{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_perry_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600313/1930122101/0164.xml":{"full_text":"BAR IS PUZZLED I\nOVER AIRLAW CODE\nRecent Conference in Wash\nington on Uniformity of Leg\nislation Develops Conflicts.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, December 30.\u2014The\nnational conference on air legislation,\nheld in Washington this week at the\ncall of Secretary of Commerce Lamont,\nbrought out sharply the fact that the j\nAmerican Bar Association has made j\nlittle progress in its long campaign for j\nnational uniformity in air laws. It;\nrevealed conflicts as between State and\nFederal laws and a general lack of ac\ncepted definitions upon which a national\nair code could be built.\nTwo delegates from each State, law\nyers and aviation specialists, attended\nthe conference. A number of these\ndelegates are stopping in New York,\nen route to their homes, conferring\nwith legal experts as to some possible\nnext step in the formulation of nation\nally uniform laws. It is believed fur\nthelr progress will lie in the co-operation\nof State Legislatures rather than through i\nFederal legislation as, the delegates\nagree, the problem involves primarily\nthe exercise of police power, which is\nthe function of the States.\nSuggests Federal Licenses.\nSo far as Federal action is concerned,\nthe only recommendation of the con\nference was that Federal licenses be re\nquired by all flyers, instead of from\nInterstate flyers only, as at present.\nThe aviation industry has weathered\nthe business depression surprisingly well\nand it is seeking the safety and sta\nbility of a clearly defined legal code.\nWhile the bar association has been\nvoluntarily working toward uniform\nstatute ssince 1020, there are still only\n21 States which require Federal licenses\nfor any and all flying. In 12 States\ncommercial flyers must have a Federal\nlicense. In sue States either a Federal\nor State license suffices. Six require\nonly a State license.\nTo conflicting and inadequate regu\nlations is attributed a considerable\nnumber of accidents and fatalities, these\nbeing much more frequent in non\nacheduled flying. In this field of avia\ntion during the first six months of\n1930, there were 144 fatal accidents in\n51,000,000 miles of flying, while in\nscheduled flying there were six fatal\naccidents in 16,000,000 miles.\nAction by Bar Association.\nAt its annual meeting in Memphis,\nTenn., two years ago, the bar associa\ntion empowered its Committeeon Aero\nnautical Law to draft a uniform code to\nbe submitted to the State Legislatures.\nThis seemed simple enough, but the sky\nlawyers began to hit air pockets when\nthey took up the constitutional sub- II\ntleties involved. Even at this late date\nthere 1s some doubt about just how far\ninto the heavens a ground sovereignty\nextends and to just what extent the\nelementary police power of a subordi\nnate political unit may be nationally\ncodified. While the lawyers have been\npuzzling over these matters, the States\nhave been passing legislation of their\nown, some of them quite unmindful of\nwhat the Federal Government might l\nor might not do. The result has been I\ndelay and confusion.\nLeading Authority Quoted.\nIt is possible that continued efforts;\nin this field will be aided and guided by\nthe vast amount of- work done by the f\nUniversity of Koenigsberg, under Dr. j I\nOtto Schrieber, leading European au- 1\nthorlty on aeronautical law. Dean I\nSommers, of the New York University' 1\nSchool of Low. has sounded the re- I\nsearch done by his European colleague: I\nand has inaugurated studies in the uni- I\nfication of air law in this university.; I\nMembers of the bar association\u2019s special f\ncommittee are co-operating with him I\nand it is hoped that within two years I\nat the most, there will be prepared some I\nimpregnable foundation for a sound 11\nlegal structure.\n(Copyright. 1930.)\nMIX DENIES DIVORCE\nCHARGES OF WIFE\nCowboy Actor\u2019s Wife Alleges Hus-\nband Swaggered and Twirled\nTwo Onns.\nBr the Associated Press.\nLOS ANGELES. December 20.\u2014Tom\nMix, fllmdom\u2019s two-gun he-man, filed II\nan answer yesterday to the divorce I\nsuit of his wife, Victoria Mix, and i\ndenied everything.\nMrs. Mix said the cowboy was a bit 1\nferocious, but Mix replied he was a'\ndocile man at home. She said he\ntwirled two guns on his \u2019'shooting\u201d\nfingers and swaggered up and down\ntheir home on the day they parted.,\nMix replied \u201cNo!\"\nThe answer was filed by his attor- i\nney, Milton M. Cohen, who said the\nfilm star was not In the city. He geld\na property settlement had been reach\ned between the couple and indicated\nthe suit would not be contested.\nInstead of ignoring the illness of j\ntheir young daughter, Tomasina, as\nhis wife charged, Mix said he always\nwas solicitous about her welfare. Mrs.\nMix said her husband refused to come j\nhome during one of his \u201cfrequent trips\u201d\nwhen she told him Tomasina was sick. j\nShe alleged he remained away from\ntheir Beverly Hills home for long pe-\nriods, declining to make any explana- i\ntkm. Mix said he offered no explana\ntion because his wife was indifferent.\nBrazil Orders Internal Loan.\nRIO DE JANEIRO. December 20 U\nt/P). \u2014In view of the difficulty some of n\nthe states are experiencing in arranging j\npayment of their external debt, the fed- H\neral government has authorized an in- II\nternal loan of >5,000,000 to aid them.\nKNABE: I\nThe\nGift\nindorsed by Music's\nimmortals and sold by\nHomer L. Kitt Co.\n1330 G St. N.W.\nMore Kants\nI The Climax of Christmas Offerings\nI \u201cFurniture of Merit\u201d\nIf there is some one still to be \u201cremembered\u201d this list will offer many suitable suggestions,\ncombining the useful with the unique\u2014and at prices which your purse will appreciate.\nWe recommend the two suite items for gifts or for personal use \u2014as being exceedingly good\ninvestments \u2014specially featured for the holidays\u20